******
[4] Israel
Date: Mon 7 Jan 2019, 2:15 PM
Source: The Yeshiva World [edited]
https://www.theyeshivaworld.com/news/israel-news/1657608/dad-with-measles-endangers-dozens-of-babies-at-mayanei-hayeshua-hospital.html


A father with measles visited the preemie ward at Bnei Brak's Mayanei HaYeshua Hospital on [Thu 3 Jan 2019] endangers dozens of Babies by entering without informing any hospital personnel he had been diagnosed with measles.

When it was learned the father was ill, staff members were quick to vaccinate over 80 babies, some only a day or 2 old.

According to the Yisrael Hayom newspaper report filed by Ron Reznik and Meital Yasur Beit-Ohr, the hospital decided to vaccinate all of the 24 preemies in the unit along with 60 babies in the adjacent unit. It is explained that since children are usually vaccinated after a year, in this case, due to the circumstances, they were given the regular vaccination and not a prophylactic treatment.

Professor Moti Ravid, director of the hospital, is quoted telling the newspaper, "This is a wild and inconsiderate act, not to mention that the same man endangered his son, along with placing other babies at risk. A guard is posted and so far, we have concentrated mainly on preventing the entry of visiting children. From now on, we will also guard the entry of adults, and we also hung signs around the hospital asking visitors with fever or a rash not to enter the hospital."

Ravid adds, "Someone who does not feel good should not visit a hospital, or shul and yeshiva for that matter".

According to Health Ministry data, up until last week, 3030 cases of measles have been diagnosed in Israel including 502 new cases which were diagnosed in December 2018.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[If the mother had her MMR shots and/or had measles infection earlier in life, or if the mother breastfeeds, antibody will be passively transferred to the newborn. Those antibodies should be protective for up to 6 months or more. For this reason, babies don't get the MMR shot earlier than 1 year old. Nonetheless, the decision to vaccinate the newborn babies was wise following the blatant disregard for their safety by the infected individual, because the immunization status of the mothers was likely unknown. - Mod.LK]

[The HealthMap/ProMED map of Israel: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=6248575,90. - Mod.MPP]

******
[5] Re: PRO/EDR, Measles vaccine - India: (MH) adverse events, RFI 20190105.6241915
Date: Tue 8 Jan 2019
From: Stephen Seligman, MD <sseligman@mail.rockefeller.edu> [edited]


Several instances of possible reactions to the MR vaccine in India were reported in a ProMED posting on 5 Jan 2019. In conjunction with studies on genetic immune defects associated with severe or unusual infections, we are studying rare, but frequently fatal, reactions to the MMR vaccine. The fatal reactions in the 1- year-old at Nagpur in Maharashtra and the 11-year-old girl, from Bhandara's Lakhni tehsil are particularly worthy of investigation to rule out such defects.

Our studies thus far have revealed defects in the type I and III IFN [interferon] signaling pathways. Investigation of additional families is ongoing.

Precise estimates of the incidence of severe reactions to the measles component of MR and MMR vaccines are not available, but are likely of the order of a few cases per million vaccinees. The benefits of the live virus measles vaccines far outweighs these rare reactions.

--
Stephen J. Seligman, MD
<sseligman@mail.rockefeller.edu>

[ProMED thanks Dr. Seligman for his comment regarding the adverse reactions to the measles vaccine.

MMR (measles, mumps, rubella) and MR (measles, rubella) are live vaccines composed of attenuated virus. Live vaccines are significantly more immunogenic than inactivated vaccines, since natural subclinical infection is imitated, thereby inducing a wide range of immunologic responses, including both humoral (B cells) and cellular (CD8+and CD4+ T cells). Furthermore, the dosage administered is low, leading to low cost of preparation and limited allergic response. Although booster inoculations are often recommended, a single vaccine administration may be sufficient to induce long-term, sometimes even lifelong, protection.

One disadvantage of live vaccines is that they may revert to natural virulence via back or compensatory mutations of the attenuated organism. This can lead to symptoms similar to wild-type virus infection in the recipient or in unprotected contacts (e.g., vaccine-associated paralytic poliomyelitis after oral poliovirus vaccine, OPV). (edited excerpt from https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/immunology-and-microbiology/live-vaccines). In addition, live vaccines are labile and generally must be maintained in a cold chain, and interference with naturally infecting agents can occur leading to vaccine failure.

However, as brought up by Dr. Seligman, above, in regard to measles, the benefits of live virus vaccines far outweigh these rare reactions. - Mod.LK]

[The HealthMap/ProMED map of India: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=6248575,142. - Mod.MPP
